 here. Don't miss out on the unique south Indian foods on this beach, such as crispy Sundal and Murukku. Tourists can visit various historic sites along the seaside to reawaken your inner adventurer. 3. Marundeeswarar Temple On the Bay of Bengal beaches lies Marundeeswarar Temple, a well-known Shiva temple in Chennai. Marundeeswarar is renowned as the 'god of medicines,' Hindu worshippers travel from across the country to pray for health and healing. The temple was erected by the 'Nayanars Appar and the Thirugnana Sambandar between the 7th and 8th centuries and is a remarkable example of typical Dravidian architecture. The Chola monarchy later preserved and popularised the temple in the 11th century. It is now one of Chennai's most popular tourist destinations, attracting pilgrims from the country. The temple's prasadam, a mixture of sacred ash, water, and milk, is said to be a cure-all for all diseases and afflictions. Lord Marundeeswarar, according to religious texts, educated the renowned Sage Agastya about the therapeutic use of several plants. As a result, a large number of people come here to seek blessings and to be cured of their diseases. The temple's prasad is also said to have medicinal properties. 4. Breezy Beach This aptly named beach, tucked away in Chennai's Valmiki Nagar region, is the perfect getaway from the city's frantic everyday life. The beach is famed for its beautiful sunrises and delicious breakfasts from nearby eateries and cafés. The location, which is around 9 kilometres from the city's heart, gives a peaceful feel to it. As it is one of Chennai's most well-known tourist spots, people flock here to take a break from their daily routine. On your journey down to the breezy beach, try roadside snacks like Sandals and Idli, which you can get at the nearby Thiruvanmiyur market. 5. Fort St. George Fort St. George, the first English fortress in India and one of the official monuments of the British Empire in Chennai, is a live symbol of British 