, rest beneath the palm trees, or watch the sunset. 2. Marina Beach The breathtaking sunrises and sunsets at Marina Beach, a renowned tourist site and a must-see on any visit to Chennai as it fascinates visitors every time. As you stroll around the world's second-biggest beach, you'll immerse yourself in deep serenity and tranquillity. Marina Beach is captivating in every way, with gorgeous palm trees surrounding it and glistening golden sand beneath your feet. Marina Beach, a God-blessed beach in South India, is the ideal escape. Cool winds never fail to rejuvenate you here. Don't miss out on the unique south Indian foods on this beach, such as crispy Sundal and Murukku. Tourists can visit various historic sites along the seaside to reawaken your inner adventurer. 3. Marundeeswarar Temple On the Bay of Bengal beaches lies Marundeeswarar Temple, a well-known Shiva temple in Chennai. Marundeeswarar is renowned as the 'god of medicines,' Hindu worshippers travel from across the country to pray for health and healing. The temple was erected by the 'Nayanars Appar and the Thirugnana Sambandar between the 7th and 8th centuries and is a remarkable example of typical Dravidian architecture. The Chola monarchy later preserved and popularised the temple in the 11th century. It is now one of Chennai's most popular tourist destinations, attracting pilgrims from the country. The temple's prasadam, a mixture of sacred ash, water, and milk, is said to be a cure-all for all diseases and afflictions. Lord Marundeeswarar, according to religious texts, educated the renowned Sage Agastya about the therapeutic use of several plants. As a result, a large number of people come here to seek blessings and to be cured of their diseases. The temple's prasad is also said to have medicinal properties. 4. Breezy Beach This aptly named beach, tucked away in Chennai's Valmiki Nagar region, is the perfect getaway from the city's frantic everyday life. The beach is famed for its beautiful sunrises 